<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_simple_extension" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Simple extensions</title>

    <definition xml:id="d_simple_extension">
        <title>Simple extension</title>
        
        <statement>
            <p>
                 Let <m>L/F</m> be a field extension. A subextension <m>K/F</m> is called a <term>simple extension</term> of <m>F</m> if <m>K=F(\alpha)</m> for some <m>\alpha\in L</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                In plain English, a simple extension of <m>F</m> is one generated over <m>F</m> by a single element. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <assumption xml:id="fiat_generated_fields">
        <title>Generated fields convention</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>F</m> be a field. In order to speak of a field of the form <m>K=F(\alpha)</m> or <m>K=F(\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\dots, \alpha_n)</m>, we technically need to introduce a larger <q>ambient</q> field <m>L/F</m> where these elements <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\alpha_i</m> are drawn from.  
            </p>
            <p>
                In situations where this ambient field <m>L</m> does not play an important role, we reserve the right to omit it from our discussion. For example, if introducing a simple field extension <m>F(\alpha)/F</m> without further details, it is assumed that in fact <m>F\leq F(\alpha)\leq L</m> for some larger field <m>L</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </assumption>
    <example xml:id="eg_simple">
        <title>Simple extensions</title>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The extension <m>\C/\R</m> is simple, since <m>\C=\R(i)</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        For any field <m>F</m>, the field of rational functions <m>F(x)</m> in one variable is a simple field extension of <m>F</m>.   
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        On the other hand it is possible to show that the field of rational functions <m>F(x,y)</m> in two variables is <em>not</em> simple: <ie/>, we do not have <m>F(x,y)=F(q)</m> for any rational function <m>q(x,y)=f(x,y)/g(x,y)</m>.
                    </p>

                </li>
                
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </example>

    <convention xml:id="not_quot_poly">
        <title>Quotients of polynomial rings</title>
            <p>
                Let <m>F</m> be a field, let <m>f(x)</m> be a nonconstant polynomial in <m>F[x]</m>, and let <m>\pi\colon F[x]\rightarrow F[x]/(f)</m> be the corresponding quotient ring homomorphism. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Since <m>\deg f\geq 1</m>, we have <m>(f)\cap F=(0)</m>, and hence the restriction of <m>\pi</m> to <m>F\leq F[x]</m> is injective. As such <m>\pi(F)\cong F</m>, and we identify <m>F</m> with its isomorphic image <m>\pi(F)\leq F[x]/(f)</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Given <m>g(x)=\bmpoly\in F[x]</m> we denote <m>\pi(g)=\overline{g}</m> for short. We have
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\overline{g} \amp =\overline{b_m}\overline{x}^m+\overline{b_{m-1}}\overline{x}^{m-1}+\cdots +\overline{b_1}\overline{x}+\overline{b_0} \amp (\pi \text{ is ring homo.})</mrow>
                            <mrow> \amp =b_m\overline{x}^m+b_{m-1}\overline{x}^{m-1}+\cdots +b_1\overline{x}+b_0  \amp (\text{identify } F \text{ with } \pi(F))</mrow>
                        </md>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
            </p>
    </convention>
    <convention xml:id="not_poly_maps">
        <title>Maps between polynomial rings</title>
        <p>
            A ring homomorphism <m>\phi\colon R\rightarrow S</m> extends naturally to a ring homomorphism 
           <m>R[x] \longrightarrow S[x]</m> that sends an <m>R</m>-polynomial <m>\anpoly</m>  to the <m>S</m>-polynomial <m>\phi(a_n)x^n+\phi(a_{n-1})x^{n-1}+\cdots +\phi(a_1)x+\phi(a_0)</m>. 
            By abuse of notation, we will also denote this map of polynonmial rings as <m>\phi</m>. Thus, given <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> we will write 
            <me>
                \phi(f)=\phi(a_n)x^n+\phi(a_{n-1})x^{n-1}+\cdots +\phi(a_1)x+\phi(a_0)
            </me>.
        </p>
    </convention>
    <theorem xml:id="th_quot_poly">
        <title>Quotients of polynomial rings</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>F</m> be a field and let <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> be a nonconstant polynomial in <m>F[x]</m>. Following <xref ref="not_quot_poly"/>, given <m>g\in F[x]</m>, we denote by <m>\overline{g}</m> its image in <m>F[x]/(f)</m> under the quotient map.   
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <title>Simply generated</title>
                        <p>
                            We have <m>F[x]/(f(x))=F[\overline{x}]</m>: <ie/>, <m>F[x]/(f)</m> is generated over <m>F</m> as a ring by <m>\overline{x}</m>, the image of <m>x</m> under the quotient map. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Dimension</title>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>n=\deg f</m>. The set <m>B=\{1,\overline{x},\dots, \overline{x}^{n-1}\}</m> is a basis of <m>F[x]/(f)</m> as a vector space over <m>F</m>, and thus <m>\dim_F F[x]/(f)=\abs{B}=n</m>.  
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Mapping property</title>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>S</m> be a nonzero ring. The set of all ring homomorphisms <m>\overline{\phi}\colon F[x]/(f)\rightarrow S</m> is in bijective correspondence with pairs <m>(\phi, s)</m> where <m>\phi\colon F\rightarrow S</m> is a ring homomorphism and <m>s\in S</m> is a root of 
                            <me>
                                \phi(f)=\phi(a_n)x^n+\phi(a_{n-1})x^{n-1}+\cdots +\phi(a_1)x+\phi(a_0)
                            </me>.
                            Indeed, given such a pair <m>(\phi, s)</m>, we define 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\overline{\phi}\colon F[x]/(f) \amp \longrightarrow S</mrow>
                                <mrow> b_m\overline{x}^m+b_{m-1}\overline{x}^{m-1}+\cdots +b_1\overline{x}+b_0 \amp\longmapsto \phi(b_m)s^m+\phi(b_{m-1})s^{m-1}+\cdots  +\phi(b_1)s+\phi(b_0) </mrow>
                            </md>.  
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                The proof of this result relies on various bits of theory from general ring theory. It is left as an (excellent) exercises. 
            </p>
        </proof>
    </theorem>
    <corollary xml:id="cor_quot_poly">
        <title>Quotients of polynomial rings</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>F</m> be a field, let <m>f(x)</m> be an irreducible polynomial of degree <m>n</m>, and let <m>K=F[x]/(f)</m>. Following <xref ref="not_quot_poly"/>, we identify <m>F</m> with its image in <m>K</m> under the quotient map. 
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>K</m> is a field and the extension <m>K/F</m> is simple. In fact, we have <m>K=F[\overline{x}]=F(\overline{x})</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We have <m>[K\colon F]=\deg f=n</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </corollary>
    <example>
        <title>Field of cardinality four</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>f(x)=x^2+x+1\in \F_2[x]</m>. Prove that <m>\F_2[x]/(f)</m> is a field of cardinality four. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Denote <m>\F_2=\{0,1\}</m>. Since <m>\deg f=2</m>, it is irreducible over <m>\F_2</m> if and only if it has a root in <m>\F_2</m>. Since <m>f(0)=f(1)=1\ne 0 </m>, we see that <m>f</m> is irreducible. Using <xref ref="cor_quot_poly"/>, we conclude that <m>K=\F_2[x]/(f)</m> is  field, and that <m>B=\{\overline{x}, 1\}</m> is a basis of <m>K</m> over <m>\F_2</m>. It follows that every element of <m>K</m> can be uniquely expressed as <m>a\overline{x}+b</m>, with <m>a,b\in \F_2</m>. There are exactly four such expressions: 
                <me>
                   0=0\overline{x}+0, 1=0\overline{x}+1, \overline{x}=1\overline{x}+0, \overline{x}+1=1\overline{x}+1  
                </me>.    
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <title>Quotients of <m>\R[x]</m></title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>f(x)\in \R[x]</m> be any irreducible quadratic polynomial. Prove that <m>\R[x]/(f)\cong \C</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since <m>f</m> is irreducible, the quotient <m>K=\R[x]/(f)</m> is a field. Since <m>\deg f=2</m>, we have <m>K=\{r+s\overline{x}\colon r,s\in\R\}</m>. Let <m>z_0\in \C</m> be a root of <m>f(x)</m>. Using <xref ref="th_quot_poly"/>, the map <m>\phi\colon K\rightarrow \C</m> defined as <m>\phi(r+s\overline{x})=r+sz_0</m> is a ring homomorphism. Furthermore, since <m>K</m> is a field, the map <m>\phi</m> is injective, and thus we have <m>K\cong \phi(K)\leq \C</m>. We claim <m>\phi(K)=\C</m>. This is a result of the fact that <m>\phi</m> is a linear transformation of <m>\R</m>-vector spaces: <ie/>, for any <m>r,s\in \R</m> and <m>\alpha=r_1+s_1\overline{x}, \beta=r_2+s_2\overline{x}</m>, we have <m>\phi(r\alpha+s\beta)=r\phi(\alpha)+s\phi(\beta)</m>, as you can easily check. It then follows that <m>K\cong \phi(K)</m> as <m>\R</m>-vector spaces, and thus that <m>\dim_\R \phi(K)=2</m>. Since <m>\phi(K)\leq \C</m> and <m>\dim_\R \phi(K)=\dim_\R \C=2</m>, we conclude that <m>\phi(K)=\C</m>.     
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <definition xml:id="d_algebraic">
        <title>Algebraic and transcendental elements</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>K/F</m> be a field extension. An element <m>\alpha\in K</m> is <term>algebraic</term> over <m>F</m> if there is a nonzero polynomial <m>f(x)\in F[x]</m> such that <m>f(\alpha)=0</m>; an element <m>\alpha\in K</m> is <term>transcendental</term> over <m>F</m> if it is not algebraic over <m>F</m>. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <theorem xml:id="th_simple_ext">
        <title>Simple extensions</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>K/F</m> be a field extension and let <m>\alpha\in K</m>.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The following statements are equivalent.
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\alpha</m> is algebraic.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>F(\alpha)\cong F[x]/(f)</m> for some irreducible polynomial <m>f(x)\in F[x]</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>F(\alpha)/F</m> is finite: <ie/>, <m>[F(\alpha)\colon F]&lt; \infty</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The following statements are equivalent.
                        <ol marker="(i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>\alpha</m> is transcendental.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>F(\alpha)\cong F(x)</m>, where <m>F(x)</m> is the field of rational functions in one variable over <m>F</m>. 
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>F(\alpha)/F</m> is infinite: <ie/>, <m>[F(\alpha)\colon F]=\infty</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                
            </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    
</section>